{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17606343","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17606343"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:11:47+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:11:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15916"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15916","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15916"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8607"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72388"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8607","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8607"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15916"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57858"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"8662"},{"type":"tags","id":"8727"},{"type":"tags","id":"8742"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20617"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20622"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72388","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72388"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring embryological development, the eye forms through complex interactions between different tissue layers.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following correctly describes the embryological origin of the retina?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Migration of neural crest cells","Derived from mesoderm","Derived from endoderm","Derived from surface ectoderm","Derived from neuroectoderm"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe retina is derived from neuroectoderm, the embryological origin of the brain and entire nervous system. From neuroectoderm the neural tube is formed. The portion of the neural tube that gives rise to the retina and other forebrain structures is called the diencephalon. Optic vesicles form as outpouchings of the diencephalon, which develop into the optic cup and subsequently the retina.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding the embryological origins of other eye structures helps explain why this is the correct answer:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeural crest cells\u003C/strong\u003E migrate to form the corneal stroma, sclera, and choroid of the eye\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMesoderm\u003C/strong\u003E develops into the extraocular muscles that control eye movement\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEndoderm\u003C/strong\u003E has no role in eye development\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESurface ectoderm\u003C/strong\u003E forms the lens placode and corneal epithelium\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The retina develops from neuroectoderm, as part of the optic vesicle.","The cornea develops from surface ectoderm and neural crest cells.","The sclera develops from mesenchyme derived from neural crest cells."],"references":["Sadler TW. Langman\u0027s Medical Embryology: Wolters Kluwer; 2015","Williams AL, Bohnsack BL. Neural crest derivatives in ocular development: discerning the eye of the storm. Birth Defects Res C Embryo Today. 2015;105(2):87-95. doi:10.1002/bdrc.21095","Heavner W, Pevny L. Eye development and retinogenesis. Cold Spring Harb Perspect Biol. 2012;4(12):a008391. Published 2012 Dec 1. doi:10.1101/cshperspect.a008391"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"5